Take Shrine used to have a higher status than [[Itsukushima Shrine]],<ref name="wwwhiroshimabunkajp-2023a">{{Cite web|title=Hiroshima Cultural Encyclopedia - Gokurakuji Mountain -|url=http://www.hiroshima-bunka.jp/english/detail/020.html|access-date=2023-12-02|website=www.hiroshima-bunka.jp}}</ref><ref name="mydaytripcom-2023a">{{Cite web|url=https://mydaytrip.com/discover/location/hayatani-shrine|access-date=2023-12-02|website=mydaytrip.com|title=Discover Hayatani Shrine}}</ref> but due to the support of the [[Taira clan]] it was eclipsed.<ref name="wwwhiroshimabunkajp-2023a" /> The two shrines used to simultaneously provide offerings in a single ceremony.<ref>{{Cite book|last1=Havens|first1=Norman|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=a_YQAQAAIAAJ&q=Hayatani+Shrine|title=An Encyclopedia of Shinto (Shinto Jiten): Kami|last2=Inoue|first2=Nobutaka|date=2006|publisher=Institute for Japanese Culture and Classics Kokugakuin University|isbn=978-4-905853-08-4|language=en}}</ref> [[Itsukushima Shrine]] is the [[Ichinomiya]],<ref>[http://eos.kokugakuin.ac.jp/modules/xwords/images/uploads/EOS070712Ab.pdf "Nationwide List of ''Ichinomiya''", p. 3] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130517061440/http://eos.kokugakuin.ac.jp/modules/xwords/images/uploads/EOS070712Ab.pdf|date=2013-05-17}}; retrieved 2012-11-20.</ref> and [[Take Shrine]] is the [[Sōja shrine]]. <ref name=":1">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=shFDAQAAIAAJ&q=%22take+shrine%22+hiroshima|title=The Japan Daily Mail|date=1899|language=en}}</ref><ref name=":2">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VB9CAQAAMAAJ&q=%22take+shrine%22+hiroshima|title=Japan Weekly Mail|date=1899|language=en}}</ref><ref name=":0">{{Cite web|title=Take Shrine Treasure House - Hiroshimatatemonogatari|url=https://www.pref.hiroshima.lg.jp/soshiki_file/tatemonogatari/en/page062.html|access-date=2023-12-02|website=www.pref.hiroshima.lg.jp}}</ref>
Hayatani Shrine is a sacred place in [[:en:Aki Province|Aki Province]] that has been worshipped for over 1,700 years. It was listed as a [[:en:Myojin Taisha|Myojin Taisha]] before the Engishiki was written, In 811 it and [[Itsukushima]] were both given the Rank by the Emperor.<ref>{{Cite web|date=2023-03-10|title=Myōjin {{!}} 國學院大學デジタルミュージアム|url=https://d-museum.kokugakuin.ac.jp/eos/detail/?id=9984|access-date=2023-12-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230310155140/https://d-museum.kokugakuin.ac.jp/eos/detail/?id=9984|archive-date=2023-03-10}}</ref> People from all over Japan visit Hayatani Shrine to pray for [[Road traffic safety|traffic safety]], especially when buying a new car.<ref name="mydaytripcom-2023a" /> == Shikinaisha (式内社) == {{List of Shikinaisha/Legend}} {| class="wikitable" style="background:#ffffff; font-size:85%" ! style="background:#a0f0a0" colspan=4 | {{ill|Engishiki Jinmyōchō|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|2=ja|3=延喜式神名帳|4=zh|5=延喜式神名帳|6=simple|7=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|2=ja|3=延喜式神名帳|4=zh|5=延喜式神名帳|6=simple|7=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|ja|延喜式神名帳|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|2=ja|3=延喜式神名帳|4=zh|5=延喜式神名帳|6=simple|7=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|2=ja|3=延喜式神名帳|4=zh|5=延喜式神名帳|6=simple|7=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Engishiki Jinmyōchō|13=User:Immanuelle/Engishiki Jinmyōchō|qq=}} ! style="background:#a0f0a0" colspan=3 | Designated Shrines ! style="background:#a0f0a0" rowspan=2 | Compilation |- style="white-space:nowrap;" ! style="background:#a0f0a0; padding-right:2.6em; padding-left:2.6em;" | Shrine Name ! style="background:#a0f0a0; padding-right:2.1em; padding-left:2.1em;" | Reading ! style="background:#a0f0a0; padding-right:2.1em; padding-left:2.1em;" | Rank ! style="background:#a0f0a0;" | Note ! style="background:#a0f0a0; padding-right:2.6em; padding-left:2.6em;" | Shrine Name ! style="background:#a0f0a0; padding-right:2.1em; padding-left:2.1em;" | Location ! style="background:#a0f0a0; padding-right:2.3em; padding-left:2.3em;" | Remarks |- |colspan=8 style="background-color:#ccffcc;"|'''[[:en:Saeki_District,_Hiroshima|Saeki]]''' 2座（並大） |- |'''速谷神社'''||hayatanino||Myojin Taisha<ref name=":5">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QmdRAAAAYAAJ&q=Hayatani+Shrine|title=Engi-shiki; Procedures of the Engi Era: Books VI-X|date=1972|publisher=Sophia University|language=en}}</ref>||Monthly rice offering||[[Hayatani Shrine]]||[[:en:Hatsukaichi|Hatsukaichi]], a suburb of [[:en:Hiroshima|Hiroshima]]<ref>{{Cite web|date=2019-03-03|title=Hayatani Jinja|url=http://yuugenguide.squarespace.com/shrines/2018/12/20/hayatani-jinja|access-date=2023-12-02|website=Yuugen 幽玄|language=en-US}}</ref>||[[Ninomiya]]<ref name="wwwhiroshimabunkajp-2023a" />||[http://21coe.kokugakuin.ac.jp/db/jinja/490201.html] |- |'''伊都伎島神社'''||itsukishimano||Myojin Taisha||||[[Itsukushima Shrine]]||[[:en:Hatsukaichi|Hatsukaichi]], a suburb of [[:en:Hiroshima|Hiroshima]]<ref name="cali-2013a">{{Cite book|jstor=j.ctt6wqfhm|title=Shinto Shrines: A Guide to the Sacred Sites of Japan's Ancient Religion|last1=Cali|first1=Joseph|last2=Dougill|first2=John|last3=Ciotti|first3=Geoff|date=2013|publisher=University of Hawai'i Press|isbn=9780824837136}}</ref>||[[Ichinomiya]]||[http://21coe.kokugakuin.ac.jp/db/jinja/490101.html] |- |colspan=8 style="background-color:#ccffcc;"|'''[[Aki District, Hiroshima|Aki]]''' 1座（大） |- |'''多家神社'''||ohoiheno||Myojin Taisha<ref name=":3" />|| ||[[Take Shrine]]||[[:en:Fuchū, Hiroshima (town)|Fuchu]], [[Aki District, Hiroshima]]||[[Sōja shrine]]<ref name=":1" /><ref name=":2" /><ref name=":0" />||[http://21coe.kokugakuin.ac.jp/db/jinja/490301.html] |}
